For the first several years, all was good, and all is good now and I am proud to be a solar energy producer, and brag it up to all who isn't. The $ savings are awesome. Where Vivint needs to improve is when the system on the roof needs to come down for housing repairs. Our house caught fire last January, no damage to the solar equipment, but it needed to be removed. The removal process was fairly effortless, a few phone calls, emails and $499.00 ( which I was told would only be $300.00 when we signed the agreement several years earlier), but that was okay. The real hardship started when it came time for re-installation. It became very clear the young folks running things in Utah had absolutely no clue who their installation crews were let alone how to schedule them to work here in Arizona. After numerous calls to the Utah office and my wife having to wait hours at the construction site in Arizona summer heat because with no solar, no electricity, thus no air conditioning, but if she was not there when the crew showed up, they would leave. Nobody told her the crew changed her appointment until later that afternoon. But eventually, the panels where put back up and the installers did a nice job. I received an email to arrange for the power company to install the meter and turn it on. The power company came out as I scheduled but they could not do it as they said there was no power to the box. The power company was able to turn their power back on to us, but not with solar. So, I started getting their expensive bills, each time with me wondering when Vivint was going to fix it. This led to more/ numerous calls to the Vivint Utah folks who conterdicted this and said it was the power companies responsiblity. But Vivint sent out a technician who inspected the wiring in the panel box who said it was all hooked up correctly. He said the wires were "Crispy" but functional. So with this, the Vivint Utah folks left it up to me to make all arrangements from there to get the power company back out to pull the switch. Vivint folks said the power company was their competition and was deliberately being difficult to discourage people from going to solar. I told this yo the power company folks who denied it, but the power company employee gave me the phone number to the installation Vivint folks but nobody returned my call. Oh, one other thing, everytime I called Utah, I could not speak with anybody but the person who was simply a messenger between me and technical personnel, which led to constant delays between calls and waiting for return calls from the messenger, which led to more questions which I had to wait for another response delay. I actually took time off work and it took an entire day of back and forth calls when I finally gave up and my last message was I was going to stop automatic payment withdrawals until the power was reconnected and to be arranged by Vivint. I paid $500  for removal and installation but I was doing all the scheduling and I was done with it. A few days later, I received an email from the power company of a scheduled appointment to reconnect, then I received an email from Vivint that they would send a Vivint tech out too for the appointment. I took time off from work to be there too as Lisa did not want anything to do with it anymore. The Vivint tech showed up first for the appointment ( not the same guy as before). He opened the power panel to find, the wires to the circuit switch where not hooked up. The power company tech waited about an hour while the Vivint tech hooked the wires up using borrowed tools from me and the power company tech. After all was hooked up, all was smooth sailing, back on solar. A few days later, the Vivint tech who came out first and inspected the crispy wires but good and all were hooked up came by the house and asked my wife if he could re- inspect the second tech's work. First tech was nothing but insulting of the second tech's workmanship to which my wife replied that at least he saved you from your careless and lazy work. I was there the entire time the second tech hooked up the wires, he was a true professional and gentleman who didn't talk down about the first tech or Vivint and with my conversation with him as he worked he is the only person with Vivint who restored my faith in the company. I wish I could remember his name, but he is a credit to Vivint. The first tech created so much headaches due to his lazy, haphazard inspection. One other thing, after the panels were removed, I received numerous emails from Vivint  that stated they detected a fault in the system. For the first few, I responded with the panels were removed. But, this didn't stop the emails. Then I got phone calls from Vivint, which I replied the panels were removed. Then I received one more call from Vivint about a fault in the system, right about the time I was trying to get Vivint to hook the wires up. So with this call, the Vivint caller said he was going to send someone out to learn why the system was not working. I accepted. No tech ever came out and I did not get anymore emails or phones about it being down, when at that time, the panels were back up and the system was actually not working.  I realize this was a long rant, and all is good now. But Vivint really needs to improve their communications and technical support in real situations as with our situation. I am sure you receive numerous service calls from customers that need to be screened by an answering employee, but with customers who have house fires or other catostrophic incident, make closer one on one communication a priority. Again, I do talk a lot to other people about solar, I mean a lot of people, and I am very happy to have solar and I praise Vivint.
